-- Italian Stocks Gain; Buzzi, CIR, Diasorin, Fiat, Fondiaria, Indesit Move
-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 2010-12-08T16:58:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-08/italian-equity-preview-amplifon-diasorin-enel-green-power-italcementi.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
increased for a second day, rising 281.51, or 1.4 percent, to
20,393.95 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Assicurazioni Generali SpA  (G IM), Italy’s biggest insurer,
increased 2.7 percent to 14.73 euros, tracking gains in European
insurance stocks.  Fondiaria-Sai SpA  (FSA IM), Italy’s second-
biggest, and its unit  Milano Assicurazioni SpA  (MI IM) rose 9.3
percent to 5.97 euros and 7.2 percent to 1.15 euros,
respectively.  Mediolanum SpA  (MED IM), the financial-services
company partly owned by Prime Minister  Silvio Berlusconi ,
advanced 3.1 percent to 3.17 euros.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) rallied 9.2 percent to 3.59
euros, leading a gauge for European banks higher. Intermonte Sim
SpA reiterated an “outperform” recommendation on the stock
ahead of the bank’s capital increase expected next January.  Buzzi Unicem SpA  (BZU IM) increased 2.2 percent to 8.16
euros after gaining 4.7 percent yesterday. Italy’s second-
biggest cement maker is among “value cases worth re-
discovering,” according to CA Cheuvreux.  CIR-Compagnie Industriali Riunite SpA  (CIR IM) dropped for
a second day this week, falling 3.3 percent to 1.39 euros. The
stock will exit the FTSE MIB after the market closes on Dec. 17,
FTSE Group said.  Diasorin SpA  (DIA IM) jumped 6 percent to 32.20 euros and
 Tod’s SpA  (TOD IM) advanced 1.7 percent to 84 euros. The stocks
are among those set to enter the FTSE MIB.  Fiat SpA  (F IM) increased 4.1 percent to 14.63 euros,
extending yesterday’s 3.5 percent gain. Agco Corp. is interested
in buying Fiat’s tractor-making unit CNH Global NV, Agco Chief
Executive Officer  Martin Richenhagen  told Italian daily MF.  Mediobanca Securities said “the separation between Fiat
auto and Fiat industrials could trigger M&A appetite.”  Exor SpA  (EXO IM), Fiat’s main shareholder, advanced 1.2
percent to 22.84 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Francesca Cinelli  in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 